<subSubSection id="B5FC653F99267070FF0E6145C0FCFE02" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="11" pageNumber="84" type="description">
<paragraph id="FD5936B499267077FF0E6145C273FACD" blockId="11.[112,648,1323,1585]" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">
<taxonomicName id="3AE64D3799267077FF0E6145C0F0FAD0" authority="Vršanský, 2009" authorityName="Vršanský" authorityYear="2009" box="[136,246,1323,1347]" class="Insecta" family="Liberiblattinidae" genus="Leptolythica" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="11" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699267077FF0E6145C0F0FAD0" box="[136,246,1323,1347]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">Leptolythica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="D4A157DD99267077FF7D6145C13DFAD0" box="[251,315,1323,1347]" pageId="11" pageNumber="84" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from all other genera in having extremely short maxillary palps (autapomorphy).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD5936B499267077FF0E610EC12DF9A2" blockId="11.[112,648,1323,1585]" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">
According to the rapid evolutionary tempo of early 
<taxonomicName id="3AE64D3799267077FFF56115C11EFA00" authorityName="Vrsansky, MOTS CLES" authorityYear="2002" box="[115,280,1403,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Liberiblattinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="11" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Liberiblattinidae</taxonomicName>
, and despite the absence of diagnostic wings, the presence of one and the same genus in localities distant in time for at least 45 Ma (the latest published record of the 
<taxonomicName id="3AE64D3799267077FF7E61A4C19CFA71" authorityName="Vrsansky, MOTS CLES" authorityYear="2002" box="[248,410,1482,1506]" class="Insecta" family="Liberiblattinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="11" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Liberiblattinidae</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName id="3AE64D3799267077FE3E61A4C0A2FA6F" authority="Vrsansky, 2004" authorityName="Vrsansky" authorityYear="2004" class="Insecta" family="Liberiblattinidae" genus="Elisamoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="11" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699267077FE3E61A4C222FA71" box="[440,548,1482,1506]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">Elisamoides</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="99774B4599267077FDAD61A4C0A2FA6F" author="VRSANSKY P." pageId="11" pageNumber="84" pagination="49 - 54" refId="ref11005" refString="VRSANSKY P. 2004. - Cretaceous Gondwanian cockroaches (Insecta, Blattaria). Entomological Problems 34 (1 - 2): 49 - 54." type="journal article" year="2004">Vršanský, 2004</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Tithonian of Shar-Teg in 
<collectingCountry id="85F1762499267077FD8F618AC26FFA6F" box="[521,617,1508,1532]" name="Mongolia" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
) is very unlikely. Thus we safely erect a new genus to include the present species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD5936B499267077FFF76224C104F9F1" blockId="11.[113,649,1610,1700]" box="[113,258,1610,1636]" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD5936B499267077FFF76207C4A4F995" blockId="11.[113,649,1610,1700]" lastBlockId="11.[675,1212,1325,1700]" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">
Head globular, with comparatively large, round eyes. Scape and pedicel very large as well as the fam.), 
<typeStatus id="225D881699267077FD4060BCC308FB70" box="[710,782,1234,1251]" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">holotype</typeStatus>
ARC-263.16: 
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699267077FC0060BCC395FB70" bold="true" box="[902,915,1234,1251]" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">A</emphasis>
, ventral view; 
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699267077FB8A60BCC41FFB70" bold="true" box="[1036,1049,1234,1251]" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">B</emphasis>
, dorsal view. Head third antennal segment; fourth segment very short. Antenna very short, with subequal, short and wide segments. Clypeus distinct. Mandibles slender, comparatively small. Labial palps distinct, coloured, with slender dense 
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699267077FCF661C5C417FA56" box="[880,1041,1451,1477]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">sensilla chaetica</emphasis>
. Maxillary palp robust, thick but short, without coloration, with few 
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699267077FD576185C372F996" box="[721,884,1515,1541]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">sensilla chaetica</emphasis>
. Apical segment the largest.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD5936B499267070FD3D6264C0FCFE02" blockId="11.[675,1212,1325,1700]" lastBlockId="12.[111,647,216,401]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">
Forelegs cursorial, with two rows of slender spurs along longitudinal posterior femoral ridge and a strong terminal spine. Few short 
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699267077FB926224C4BFF9F7" box="[1044,1209,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="84">sensilla chaetica</emphasis>
present on the anterior margin. Tibia short, with strong spurs. Tarsi very short and robust, with dense 
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699217070FF3464B6C157FF61" box="[178,337,216,242]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="85">sensilla chaetica</emphasis>
. Mid legs with comparatively short coxa, well-developed trochanter and robust femur and tibia. Femur with long 
<emphasis id="CF92EAA699217070FE626579C281FEA2" box="[484,647,279,305]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="85">sensilla chaetica</emphasis>
on posterior, and short ones on anterior margins. Two longitudinal median ridges present.Tibia with strong spurs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B5FC653F99217070FFF765D8C18FFD7D" pageId="12" pageNumber="85" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FD5936B499217070FFF765D8C0D3FE5D" blockId="12.[111,647,438,750]" box="[113,213,438,464]" pageId="12" pageNumber="85">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD5936B499217070FFF765BBC173FDDC" blockId="12.[111,647,438,750]" pageId="12" pageNumber="85">Robust foreleg tibia with massive tarsi and robust maxillary palps are unique autapomorphies, eventually linked with the life within forest litter and/ or, possibly, for digging.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD5936B499217070FF0E663AC18FFD7D" blockId="12.[111,647,438,750]" pageId="12" pageNumber="85">
Due to the absence of diagnostic wings, no relationships can be established. The general habitus indicates relationship with the Late Jurassic undescribed small 
<taxonomicName id="3AE64D3799217070FF7B66DDC1ABFD5D" authorityName="Vrsansky, MOTS CLES" authorityYear="2002" box="[253,429,691,718]" class="Insecta" family="Liberiblattinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="12" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Liberiblattinidae</taxonomicName>
from the Karabastau Formation (unpublished).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
